The Economy of Violence
KOPENHAGEN – What is the greatest source of violence in our world?
Brutal conflicts in Syria, in Ukraine and elsewhere are constantly in the news and therefore many would probably say war.
Yet this turns out to be a great mistake.
The correct answer plays a role when we want to find cost-efficient solutions for this and other global problems.
It goes without saying that everyone would gladly end war and violence, just as we would like to put an end to poverty, hunger, and global warming and provide everyone with access to education.
Yet given limited resources, there are limits to what the international community can do.
We must set priorities, and for that one can use an economic cost-benefit analysis.
The international community is working on new development goals for the next 15 years, and the Copenhagen Consensus has asked some of the leading economists in the world to assess which goals, in their view, would be the wisest.
Is the goal of reducing violence worth the use of resources that would otherwise, for example, flow into the fight against hunger?
And, if so, which forms of violence should be targeted?
According to a study by James Fearon from Stanford University and Anke Höffler from the Center for the Study of African Economies at Oxford University, violence in society—murders and particularly violence against women and children—presents a far greater problem than civil wars.
For every death on the battlefield of a civil war, nine people die as a result of interpersonal violence, and for every two combatants who die, one child is killed.
In 2008, 418,000 people were killed worldwide, and too many countries report murder rates of more than 10 victims per 100,000 inhabitants, which the World Health Organization describes as an epidemic.
A single murder in America costs a person's life and society $9.1 million.
Measured against the national income worldwide, this form of violent crime alone costs 1.7% of the global gross social product (GDP).
Of course, this is not a direct financial loss for the global economy, but rather a way of expressing the consequences.
If murder were abolished, societies around the world would be better off in a way that could be measured by 1.7% of GDP.
Compare this with the significantly lower costs of civil wars, which correspond to about 0.2% of global GDP.
That is, however, still much less than the greatest source of violence altogether: domestic violence against women.
Based on studies published in the scientific journal Science, 28% of all women in sub-Saharan Africa experienced violence from their intimate partners or family members in the past year.
This includes women who were beaten, forced into early marriages, subjected to sexual violence, victims of crimes in the name of "honor," and subjected to genital mutilation.
According to a cautious estimate, the societal costs of violence by partners amount to $440 billion or 5.2% of global GDP.
The second-largest source of violence is child abuse, which is committed by parents in 80% of cases.
The definition of child abuse varies from culture to culture, but roughly 15% of children suffer what the UN defines as severe physical punishment each month.
This includes hitting the face, head, or ears, and a quarter of these children are hit repeatedly and as violently as possible with an object.
Every month, this suffering affects approximately 290 million children.
The social costs amount to $360 billion or 4.2% of global GDP.
A tiny fraction of international aid funds currently flows into reducing violence in society and improving criminal justice systems.
The enormous costs borne by society and by individuals scream out for something to be done.
Unfortunately, there are still few secure insights into where the limited resources should be best applied.
Everything that can be said is that the money spent on reducing violence could be used more effectively.
Large sums of aid money are allocated to "fragile states" to help end or prevent civil wars, yet only 0.27% of international aid goes to projects with the component "crime prevention."
Other programs may contribute indirectly, but it is clearly possible to do much better.
Some solutions, as is clear, work very well.
More capable social institutions can reduce child violence.
Studies in the U.S. state of Washington have shown that home visits by trained staff can reduce child abuse, improve children's quality of life and their physical and mental health, and reduce the costs of child welfare and legal proceedings.
A dollar spent on this program produces a benefit worth $14: it is therefore an extremely cost-effective measure.
In many cases, societal attitudes must change.
To reduce violence against women and girls, a program in Uganda named SASA! is working.
(Kisuaheli for "Now!") promotes the view that violence in partnerships is unacceptable and has contributed to halving the number of cases.
That is a fantastic result, even though there is no analysis of cost-efficiency available.
There are examples from other countries where effective measures have been taken.
In 1993, there were 80 murders per 100,000 inhabitants in Bogotá.
With a comprehensive approach—including a time limit on alcohol sales, the reclaiming of public space, and improvements in the police and justice system—the murder rate was reduced to 21 victims per 100,000 inhabitants in 2004.
That is still a high number, but well below the murder rate of 55 victims per 100,000 inhabitants in Detroit.
Alcohol plays a role in many violent attacks, and the insights from Bogotá suggest that controlling its availability could be of major significance.
In the United Kingdom, a pilot study on the better enforcement of existing regulations showed that violent attacks could be reduced in a very cost-efficient manner, with the benefit outweighing the costs by a ratio of 17 to 1.
We know that we still do not have enough information, but two points are clear: First, domestic violence against women and children brings with it costs of 8 billion US Dollars per year to society and thus represents a huge – and far too little noticed – global problem.
Secondly, there are solutions that can help address some of these problems in a very cost-effective manner.
For this reason, the reduction of domestic violence should be included in the shortlist of global development goals for the coming years.
